ure the impact of the epidemic because of the large populations in the region. The Report also stresses the need for data to understand the epidemic better and respond effectively. A recent editorial in the AIDS Journal and accompanying papers also highlighted the utility of household impact studies and the need for a strategic approach. 3 Socio-economic impact of HIV and AIDS in India; UNDP, NCAER & NACO, 2006 1 Socio-economic impact of HIV at the household levels in Asia and the Pacific DAy 1 D ay 14 comprised learning from the socio-economic impact studies in India and China followed by updates on the methodology and process from the research teams from five countries: India, China, Indonesia, Vietnam and Cambodia. The sessions also discussed emerging issues such as HIV and food security in Asia, impact of financial crisis on the households of People Living with HIV (PLHIV) and intimate partner transmission. OVERVIEW OF STUDy METHODOLOGIES & LEARNING: INDIA & CHINA EMERGING ISSUES AND THEIR SOCIO-ECONOMIC IMPACT 4 Please see annexure (1) for more details Introduction and setting the context I n his opening remarks, Mr. Omar Noman, Chief of Policies and Programmes, UNDP Regional Centre in Colombo, looked at the broad macro-economic situation in Asia. Making a comparison between the current global financial crisis and the Asian crisis in the late 1990s, he said there is hope in this region because unlike in the past, the financial sector hasn\u2019t collapsed. China and other countries in the region have built up huge foreign exchange reserves that can act as buffers. Delving the possible linkage between the present economic crisis and HIV, Mr. Noman talked about the major fiscal expansion which every country in this region is going through to stimulate the economy. As quite a bit of these stimulus packages are typically targeted towards social protection, in the form of public works programme or employment guarantee schemes, he felt that countries could look for stimulus packages that could protect the interest of people living with HIV. In his view, this bad time could provide very good opportunity not only to make a case for HIV, but also expand it, since at least to some extent the response to HIV/AIDS is related to government spending. Mr. Noman expressed his concern over the shortage of data and how policy responses are hampered by the non-availability and delay of data. In this context, he appreciated the socio economic impact studies that are being undertaken in the region as \u201csome- thing invaluable\u201d. He called it a great opportunity to change the policy in a substantial manner, if one could get that kind of household data for policy - formulation and match that to what may be considered to be key protection packages as fiscal stimulus. Setting the context of the consultation, Ms. Caitlin Wiesen, HIV/AIDS Regional Prac- tice Leader and Programme Coordinator, Asia and Pacific, UNDP Regional Centre in Colombo, emphasized the need to understand the socio-economic impact of HIV at the household and individual levels. In her opinion, assessing the impact of HIV/AIDS is extremely important and critical for the policies and programmes in the region. She explained how the data available can be used to address and shape the issues that often protect the interests of people living with HIV/AIDS. Though Asia is considered to be a low prevalence region, the studies in countries such as India and China indicate clearly what is happening to households with people living with HIV. Ms. Wiesen highlighted the dynamics of the epidemic in a typical Asian country as an important issue. The 75 million men in Asia who are estimated to be visiting sex workers are the key drivers in determining the phase of the epidemic. These men who visit 10 million sex workers can in turn infect 50 million women who are in marriage or long term partnership with them. This is overlapped by men who have sex with 3 Socio-economic impact of HIV at the household levels in Asia and the Pacific men and injecting drug users. In this context, Ms. Wiesen emphasized the need to look at the questions on spousal transmission and issues such as disclosure of HIV status that could be included in the socio-economic impact studies. There is also a need for serious enquiries concerning discordant couples and intimate partner violence in the context of spousal transmission. Ms. Wiesen also spoke about the impact of external shocks such as food price infla- tion", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "56d4e467-ff98-40c8-8695-673825df8e99": {"__data__": {"id_": "56d4e467-ff98-40c8-8695-673825df8e99", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/socio-economic-impact-hiv-household-levels-asia-and-pacific-report-technical-consultation", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Socio-economic impact of HIV at the household levels in Asia and the Pacific - Report on Technical Consultation", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/socio-economic-impact-hiv-household-levels-asia-and-pacific-report-technical-consultation", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "7a0f107c1c7ef7bcec18786f6fc68a611a650af76418ba86f4d83618f80aa69f"}}, "hash": "7a0f107c1c7ef7bcec18786f6fc68a611a650af76418ba86f4d83618f80aa69f", "text": "and volatility. Studies have shown that HIV households lose income due to loss of employment and their medical expenses increase significantly resulting in a decline in food consumption. This is particularly important and a cause for concern since there is a need to enhance the quantity and quality of food as lack of nutrition can lead to more rapid progression of HIV. A five country analysis undertaken by the HIV Team using existing data shows how food price increase can affect the HIV households and how food support programmes can mitigate the impact. For example, in Cambodia the HIV households who received intervention from the food support programme showed an increase in terms of quantity and quality of food intake, reduction in medical expenditure, and a positive impact on children\u2019s education. Those who have more disposable income do not compromise on quality or quantity of food. These findings are extremely important for the policy makers, she added. The Commission on AIDS in Asia has recommended that impact mitigation should be included in AIDS programmes and one of the areas that was recommended was the need to ensure livelihood options for the HIV-widows and the affected families, and to secure inheritance and property rights for women. These two recommendations are essentially based on the studies in India which shows that 80 % of women whose husbands have died were pushed out of their marital homes. Shelter and security are absolutely critical for women living with HIV. The Commission on AIDS in Asia has included this as the overall recommendation for the region and spousal transmission as a new area to concentrate on. Updating on the progress of the socio-economic impact studies, Ms. Wiesen said that the study in India was completed three years ago and it might be the right time for a follow up with a rapid survey to collect data from some of the households to measure the changes in the impact over time. China has completed the data collec- tion and analyses and is finalizing the report. In Cambodia, the questionnaire is in the final stage and emerging critical issues need to be added, without overloading it. The study in Indonesia is just getting underway and Vietnam is ready with the first draft of the report. 4 RepoRT on TeChniCal ConsulTaTion Socio-economic impact of HIV and AIDS on households in India A study in six high prevalence states: learning and experience Dr. Basantha K.Pradhan National Council for Applied Economic Research, New Delhi, India T he study on the socio-economic impact of HIV and AIDS in India was initi- ated during 2004-05 and the report published in May 2006. At that time, no large scale household survey had been done anywhere in the world on HIV and AIDS. In any survey, data is a major problem and this is more so in respect of HIV house- holds. The economic and social impact was looked at three levels: macro, household and individual levels. The data collected from households included information from household as well as individual levels (gender impact, stigma and discrimination etc). There was an attempt to assess the macro economic impact by using a mathematical model, but due to shortage of data, it encountered many problems. The objective of the study was to analyse the nature and type of socio-economic impact of HIV and AIDS on households and individuals in terms of: impact on household income and expenditure; D changes in pattern of household consumption, savings and borrowings D impact on education of children D effect on health status of PLHIV D stigma and discrimination experienced by PLHIV (an attempt was also made D to quantify this, but the results were not fully satisfactory) Gender impact of HIV and AIDS. D 5 Socio-economic impact of HIV at the household levels in Asia and the Pacific The Process The study was conducted in six high prevalence states and in each state, the districts with high prevalence were chosen. The methodology adopted was to survey HIV households as well as similar non-HIV/general households as a control group using multi-level, stratified sampling. Although listing of HIV households was available with some agencies, they could not be accessed due to ethical and confidentiality issues and therefore random sampling could not be done. In view of such constraints, VCTC counselors working in state health organizations were chosen to conduct the survey and they were trained appropriately. A team comprising a male and a female counselor was deployed in each of the selected districts. They were told to look for HIV positive individuals in clinical stages 2, 3 and 4 so that", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "074b6e77-bcf6-468b-bd3b-e3e32339a467": {"__data__": {"id_": "074b6e77-bcf6-468b-bd3b-e3e32339a467", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/socio-economic-impact-hiv-household-levels-asia-and-pacific-report-technical-consultation", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Socio-economic impact of HIV at the household levels in Asia and the Pacific - Report on Technical Consultation", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/socio-economic-impact-hiv-household-levels-asia-and-pacific-report-technical-consultation", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "16f45f60f3a60cf727fe4d6e75de8b0993a1b2c1cb006ee3c37a616f63f13e8d"}}, "hash": "16f45f60f3a60cf727fe4d6e75de8b0993a1b2c1cb006ee3c37a616f63f13e8d", "text": "the impact on the parameters to be studied was measureable. The counselors were also asked specifically to look for households in higher income groups so that the samples would be representative. However, it was not possible to get them since they don\u2019t visit government hospitals and instead seek treatment from the private sector. Hence, the sample was mainly from the lower middle and poor economic sections. The total sample consisted of 2068 HIV (rural+urban) households, and nearly three times this size, i.e. 6224 samples, were from non-HIV households serving as the control group. For every HIV household surveyed in a village/block, three non-HIV households belonging to similar localities and similar socio-economic background such as income, occupation and education were interviewed. However, the concept of obtaining similarly educated sample was not possible as numbers became too small due to sub-categorization. A list of the non-HIV households was made, with income and occupation, and if there were more than three non-HIV households with similar characteristics available for one HIV household, then, the non-HIV households were selected randomly. For the quantitative survey, two sets of questionnaires were devised, one for the HIV households, and the other for the non-HIV households. They were generally similar, except for a few questions. The HIV household questionnaire had an additional sec- tion with questions aimed at the HIV affected, and the non-HIV household question- naire had a section on knowledge and awareness about HIV/AIDS. Apart from this, Focus Group Discussions were held in different states and a number of case studies conducted to capture interesting cases on stigma and discrimination and gender issues. Results from these were used to complement the findings of the survey. The average household income was nearly same/marginally different, for the HIV and non-HIV households, and because of this, comparisons between the two could 6 RepoRT on TeChniCal ConsulTaTion be made by using different income groups. The HIV households were worse off in terms of basic amenities and ownership of assets and consumer durables. Most of the sample PLHIV was in 20-40 years age group, and the level of education was low, with nearly a fourth of the sample being illiterate. Wage labourers dominated the sample among both men and women. In terms of the findings of the study, it may be noted that no statistical analysis was undertaken. The analysis was drawn from the tables. Impact on household income The impact on the household income was through loss of job of the PLHIV and absence from work. In the present situation of the global economic meltdown, the main impact of the household will be through loss of employment. Hence, in the model questionnaire, differentiation should be made between job loss due to global meltdown and that due to HIV. In the study, the results revealed that some households did not suffer any loss of income, and one possible reason could be that the PLHIV was at an early stage of the infection, which might not have hampered the earning capacity. However, for those households which experienced a loss of income, the loss was very high and it was particularly so in respect of agricultural labourers. Also, contrary to what is found in literature, loss of income of caregivers was not very significant. This could be due to the need for supplementary income dominating the care-giving role. Also, with a person being infected with HIV, the requirement for resources increases, and this forces other members, including caregivers, to earn. Impact on employment The most severe impact of HIV on the households comes from the loss of employment caused by HIV infection. The percentage of unemployed among the PLHIV increased nearly three times: from 3.6% (before learning about their HIV status) to 9.8% (pres- ent). Work force participation rate of children and the elderly in HIV households was seen to be higher than those for non-HIV households. The requirement of resources goes up in the HIV households and hence more children and elderly are forced to work. The elderly in the HIV households are under considerable stress to look after the needs of the households. A look at gender and workforce participation rates indicates that the burden is more on women and girl children. 7 Socio-economic impact of HIV at the household levels in Asia and the Pacific Impact on the pattern of consumption The consumption pattern of certain critical components indicates the differences between HIV and non-HIV households. Medical expenses of HIV households are very high, as expected, and are almost four times that of non-HIV households. The overall food-related expenditure of HIV households is higher than that of non-HIV households,", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "ee330356-a955-461e-90c2-c5c1424aca1c": {"__data__": {"id_": "ee330356-a955-461e-90c2-c5c1424aca1c", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/socio-economic-impact-hiv-household-levels-asia-and-pacific-report-technical-consultation", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Socio-economic impact of HIV at the household levels in Asia and the Pacific - Report on Technical Consultation", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/socio-economic-impact-hiv-household-levels-asia-and-pacific-report-technical-consultation", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "f3c196c0e93045886ec2dd177634430f0fee3b4ab7aa0f0acb43e3e5c388976b"}}, "hash": "f3c196c0e93045886ec2dd177634430f0fee3b4ab7aa0f0acb43e3e5c388976b", "text": "possibly because an HIV positive person is expected to consume nutritious food to stay healthy. In order to meet this higher expenditure, the HIV households are seen to be cutting down expenditure on other items. However, closer examination reveals that in labour households, food-related expenditure is less than that in non-HIV households, indicating their inability to spend on nutritious food. Impact on household savings The HIV households had more savings in cash, indicating the need for immediate liquidity for emergencies. They hardly had any savings in jewellery and other assets. Impact on borrowings The percentage of HIV households which borrowed during the one year period before the survey was higher for HIV households at all levels of income. However, it is possible that some households might not have borrowed that year, but have done so in the previous years. In fact, the important parameter is the quantity of borrowing since a family member was tested positive. Obtaining correct information in this regard could be difficult because of recall problems. Impact on education of children The impact on education was assessed by comparing children of HIV with non-HIV households in terms of ever and current enrolment percentages, dropout rate and number of years of schooling, reasons for dropout, type of school attended, school attendance and reasons for absenteeism. In the literature on HIV/AIDS, education is a dominant subject, and reasons for dropout are generally discussed. With that in view, questions on all the above were included. Looking at both ever-enrolled and currently-enrolled, the results indicate that the non-HIV households are better off. Further, it was seen that in HIV households, more girls go to government schools than private schools because education is free in the former. 5 SNA - System of National Accounts. SNA activities are economic activities; extended SNA are para economic and non-SNA are social and cultural activities. SNA is a system of classifying activities for national accounting purposes 8 RepoRT on TeChniCal ConsulTaTion Stigma and discrimination An attempt was made to quantify stigma and discrimination experienced by the PLHIV. Surprisingly, the survey results did not indicate a high degree of discrimination at work place, school and community. This does not mean that there was no discrimination. The reason however turned out to be that most of the PLHIV had not revealed their status in these places because of the fear of stigma. In fact, even in the households, sometimes the HIV status was not disclosed even to spouses for quite sometime. Al- though a high percentage of PLHIV reported family support, in case of women it was mostly the natal family and not the in-laws. The survey revealed that women faced more discrimination - not only are a higher percentage of women asked to leave their houses compared to men, women also reported discrimination in the form of neglect, isolation, verbal teasing and deprivation of basic amenities. Gender impact In order to get the gender impact, data on the time- use- pattern was collected, in which all the members of the households were asked how they spent their time (24hours) in a day. The activities were classified into three main divisions -SNA5, which is paid work; extended SNA which involves housework, but unpaid e.g. cooking, taking care of the children); and non-SNA where the time is spent on oneself (e.g. bathing, leisure etc). The results were tabulated for two categories of family members - 15 to 59 years and above 59 years, and comparisons were made between HIV and non-HIV, male and female and elderly and others. The results revealed that men spent more time on SNA activities in both HIV and non-HIV households. Women from HIV households spent more time on productive activities. Older women of HIV households spent more time on extended SNA activities compared to their counterparts, indicating that they shoulder the additional burden of tending to the sick. Also, women from HIV households are left with lesser time for themselves. It was found that 70% of the caregivers were women and among them 21% were HIV positive themselves. 32% of female care givers were currently employed. In other words, this group of 32% women bore the burden of care and paid work, in addition to household chores. Status of HIV positive widows The impact on widows was found to be extremely severe. As compared to other HIV households, HIV widow households were worse off in terms of living conditions, as- sets, income and expenditure. The HIV widow households spent less on food, faced 9 Socio-economic impact of HIV at the household levels in Asia and the Pacific the double burden of stigma", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "ef9633fc-0e74-4c76-b326-6f8ada373abb": {"__data__": {"id_": "ef9633fc-0e74-4c76-b326-6f8ada373abb", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/socio-economic-impact-hiv-household-levels-asia-and-pacific-report-technical-consultation", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Socio-economic impact of HIV at the household levels in Asia and the Pacific - Report on Technical Consultation", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/socio-economic-impact-hiv-household-levels-asia-and-pacific-report-technical-consultation", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "5e398331bfe0b2b891f98f6945db624d3f5b423a5077931b924cbb0dcfee22b2"}}, "hash": "5e398331bfe0b2b891f98f6945db624d3f5b423a5077931b924cbb0dcfee22b2", "text": "and discrimination even in the family, and in a large number of cases, denied share in their husband\u2019s property and were living with their natal families after the death of their husbands. Discussion The key points raised during the discussion following the presentation were social protection of PLHIV for loss of income, loss of employment and methodological issues such as the challenges in the correct assessment of income. The loss of efficiency, absenteeism and loss of jobs are generally the means of loss of income. At the time of the survey, there were not many government programmers. But of late, the PLHIV in the high prevalence states are getting free ART in the government hospitals. Additionally, many NGOs in the high prevalence states provide supplementary nutritious food to some of the affected. Currently, employment guarantee schemes are being run by the government, but given the health conditions of the positive persons, it is difficult to know what kind of benefits they are likely to get out of this scheme. However, during the survey, it was found that some of the PLHIV were getting employment in the state AIDS control societies and NGOS, and widows were gainfully employed as counselors. As regards the data on household income, it is difficult to get the estimates of income correctly. Even if the income is well estimated, it generally falls short of the real income. It is possible that respondents may not understand the meaning of \u201cincome\u201d correctly. Some may not disclose all the sources of income. Hence, an indirect method of finding the income is the best, and would have the least error. Hence, information was sought individually on all sources that could constitute the total income. Now, with the emerg- ing three new issues to be incorporated into the questionnaire, many questions have to be added. But adding these questions should not make the questionnaire too lengthy. It should be balanced without losing sight of the fact that getting correct information on income is very important. In the Indian study, no statistical analysis was done, and the analysis was based only on the conclusions drawn from tables. However, they may be included in the ongoing studies. There could be significance tests - which would help in knowing whether a particular result is statistically significant or not. To study some relationships, say, the co-relationship coefficients which can be used to make comparisons, for example, whether health and education are more strongly related in HIV households than non-HIV households can be made. Regression analysis, i.e., multiple regression analysis, is very important. It can quantify the degree of dependence of a certain parameter - say how the average education level may depend on various factors like income etc. Statistical analysis of the results has already been undertaken in the China study, and should be done for all the countries. 10 RepoRT on TeChniCal ConsulTaTion Socio-economic impact of HIV at the household levels in China A five province study: learning and experience Prof. Yuan Jianhua Beijing Institute of Information Control, Beijing, China I n China, 223,501 persons were reportedly living with HIV/AIDS until the end of 2007, most of them in rural areas. Even though the overall prevalence of HIV and AIDS is low in China, the prevalence rate is fairly high among special population groups and in certain areas. Studies indicate that the socio-economic impact of HIV at individual and household levels can be very severe at some places. However, there is not enough data and evidence which quantify the impact of and response to HIV and AIDS on households and individuals. A household survey to assess the socio-economic impact was conducted during February - April 2008 with the support of UNDP in five high HIV prevalence provinces in China, namely Yunnan, Guangxi, Sichuan, Hubei and Shanxi. This included survey of HIV households (target group) and non-HIV households (control group). Please see companion CD-ROM for the questionnaire. The Process The tools of the survey included structured questionnaire for data collection, fo- cus group discussions, case study etc. The questionnaire was based on the India questionnaire with inputs from Dr. Pradhan. The sample households were selected by using multi-stage sampling method and, at each stage, selection was based on systematic sampling. The sampling framework is the list of PLHIV who can be contacted in the locality. The non-HIV positive persons whose age were almost the same as HIV persons (less than five years old) were selected as the control group in the neighborhood of the PLHIV interviewed or in the community where HIV posi- tive persons lived. The sample consisted of 931 HIV households", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "9acfcc27-877d-41fd-976b-41f755c899de": {"__data__": {"id_": "9acfcc27-877d-41fd-976b-41f755c899de", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/socio-economic-impact-hiv-household-levels-asia-and-pacific-report-technical-consultation", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Socio-economic impact of HIV at the household levels in Asia and the Pacific - Report on Technical Consultation", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/socio-economic-impact-hiv-household-levels-asia-and-pacific-report-technical-consultation", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "e9dcdf921362a73a89020f5ed2f5b650a818ecde8457096a7b6cb64ddefd2189"}, "3": {"node_id": "00578074-0d3d-4ae1-80c3-0aa29d33c685", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/socio-economic-impact-hiv-household-levels-asia-and-pacific-report-technical-consultation", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "d28dba87916da9dd8c5e326d0751b32399ca9f53f0e32bbb10ae159718c68719"}}, "hash": "221e85c5a741651d897104df279d0362160bf61a1d341b7f2a077484cd9cda29", "text": "(1027 PLHIV) and 995 non-HIV households. The survey was conducted in collaboration with local departments, such as CDC and Women Union and some of the PLHIV participated as investigators. The SPSS statistical 11 Socio-economic impact of HIV at the household levels in Asia and the Pacific package was used for analyzing the data. The statistical analysis methods included: descriptive statistics, table analysis, mean comparison, correlation and regression analysis. The research team conducted panel discussions for the technical report a number of times, so as to find more information and quantify the correctness of the conclusions. Dr. Pradhan provided technical support and a number of multiple analyses were carried out and these included in the detailed report. Information was shared with officials from the UN agencies and government sectors. Based on the analysis of data and technical report, a detailed report and a summary report have been finalized. The research team conducted five consultative meetings with experts from the government departments, CDC, international agencies, NGOs and universities and the participants proposed some recommendations to the report, which were very valuable and helpful. Key findings HIV/AIDS could change the household structure. 41.1 percent of the HIV D households surveyed are in joint-family (married children living with parents/ grandparents), while in the case of non-HIV households this percentage is lower at around 33.4%. Distribution of households by level of income shows that while nearly half of D the HIV households belong to the low income category (household annual income less than 10,000 Yuan) and 19.26 % live under the relative poverty line (household annual income less than 4193 Yuan), in the case of non-HIV house- holds only one third belongs to the low income category and 11.46% of the households live under the relative poverty line. An analysis of the consumption pattern reveals that the expenditure of HIV D households is mostly focused on the basic needs of daily life. Compared to non-HIV households, the HIV household spends 17.4 percent of the total con- sumption on medical expenditure, about 10 percent higher than the percent- age of non-HIV households (7.9%), and the expenditure on education and durables is much lower The survey attempted to find out the mechanisms adopted by the HIV house- D holds to cope with the financial difficulties. Most of the HIV households have no insurance or pension. When facing financial crisis, the first choice for both HIV and non-HIV households is to borrow from friends and relatives (60.7% and 66.7%), the second choice is to use up the savings (25.5% and 32.7%). The proportion of households resorting to liquidation of assets, spouse going out to work to earn additional income and receiving support from the NGOs are higher in the case of HIV households. 12 RepoRT on TeChniCal ConsulTaTion The impact of HIV/AIDS on education of children mostly happened in the D households belonging to low income category and those live below the rela- tive poverty line. Compared to respondents from non-HIV households, the PLHIV spent less D time in productive work; the time spent by male PLHIV on productive work is 42 percent less than that of non-HIV positive male, while in the case of female PLHIV it was 28% less, indicating that female PLHIV could not reduce their working time as much as men could. As far as the total time spent on produc- tive work and household work is concerned, the women in non-HIV house- holds spend 0.7 hours more than men, while female PLHIV work 2.2 hours more than male PLHIV, indicating that HIV/AIDS increases the work pressure for females, while men could get more time for relaxation. Regression analysis was also done to find the impact of various factors on D the quality of life of the PLHIV. Ten independent variables such as per capita income, CD4 count, education, discrimination and marital status were used for the analysis. The most important variable which had a negative impact on the quality of life turned out to be discrimination in the community. The per capita income had a positive impact. Conclusion HIV/AIDS could impact the household economy a lot, such as the drop or loss D of physical ability of PLHIV, the loss of employment opportunities, and the reduction of personal income. As a result, more HIV households fall under low income category.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "00578074-0d3d-4ae1-80c3-0aa29d33c685": {"__data__": {"id_": "00578074-0d3d-4ae1-80c3-0aa29d33c685", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/socio-economic-impact-hiv-household-levels-asia-and-pacific-report-technical-consultation", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Socio-economic impact of HIV at the household levels in Asia and the Pacific - Report on Technical Consultation", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/socio-economic-impact-hiv-household-levels-asia-and-pacific-report-technical-consultation", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "e9dcdf921362a73a89020f5ed2f5b650a818ecde8457096a7b6cb64ddefd2189"}, "2": {"node_id": "9acfcc27-877d-41fd-976b-41f755c899de", "node_type": null, "