mbine various recourses to provide day-to-day support to the families of D PLHIV, especially the families with single parent and old people. This would help in reducing the stress and improving the quality of life of the family. In the high prevalence areas, combine anti-discrimination education with D IEC activities. The aim of such education should not only be to promote the knowledge of HIV/AIDS, but also to change the attitude and behavior of people towards PLHIV by conducting specific activities. Strengthen the interventions on education of children, especially for girls. D Establish a targeted education support system. Adjust the contents of \u201cFour Free and One Care\u201d policy, provide education support and free skill training for older children. Pay more attention to female PLHIV. Take up targeted measures to reduce D their vulnerability. 14 RepoRT on TeChniCal ConsulTaTion Discussion The discussion mainly focused on methodological and data collection challenges such as maintenance of confidentiality, incentives for the respondents in view of the long questionnaire and time taken for interviews and difference between rural and urban HIV households. In response, Prof. Yuan said that the local CDC has the list of names and the field work was done in cooperation with them. One or two days before the interview, the local CDC fixed up appointments with them. Before the interview, they were informed that this was only for research and not open to public. In the questionnaire, the name of the person was not written, but only the names of the contact people were mentioned. In the Union province, since there is no discrimination, the field team directly went to their houses. This study was mostly conducted in villages, except in two places, which were like a township. He also said the respondents were given nominal amounts of money. It was suggested that sector-wise impact may be measured in the future studies particularly in view of the impact of the economic crisis on people living with HIV. It was also stated that in both India and China, family members were not allowed to be present during the interview of the PLHIV. Their presence may actually affect the interview process and disclosure of complete/correct information. In both the countries, the control group was selected from similar socio-economic backgrounds. In Cambodia and Vietnam, closest (proximity) household method was used for se- lecting the control group. In this context, some literature review can be done to see how technically/comparatively valid they are. The participants suggested additional analysis of secondary information, e.g. review of existing government policies and support and whether the numbers match with the government support. 15 Socio-economic impact of HIV at the household levels in Asia and the Pacific Socio-economic impact of HIV in Indonesia A seven province study: update on the methodology and the process Mr. Teguh Pramono Central Bureau of Statistics, Jakarta, Indonesia I ndonesia consists of 33 provinces, spread out from Aceh in the north-west and Papua in the far- east.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "6de8bff1-0b83-47d2-bf65-5b32e9de56bb": {"__data__": {"id_": "6de8bff1-0b83-47d2-bf65-5b32e9de56bb", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/socio-economic-impact-hiv-household-levels-asia-and-pacific-report-technical-consultation", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Socio-economic impact of HIV at the household levels in Asia and the Pacific - Report on Technical Consultation", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/as