ata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/socio-economic-impact-hiv-household-levels-asia-and-pacific-report-technical-consultation", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "01201cb2d1d43cc54cec6373df27deac3ce9013bde8304048a954ec38718a7d9"}}, "hash": "01201cb2d1d43cc54cec6373df27deac3ce9013bde8304048a954ec38718a7d9", "text": "to Jakarta; West Java; and North Sumatra. The purpose of the study is to create a detailed report on the nature and extent of socio-economic impact of HIV on individuals and households and recommendations for impact mitigation. The study will focus on household structure, income, expendi- ture, employment, health, education, access to services, interpersonal relationships, stigma and discrimination, the impact of rising food-prices, psychological impact, quality of life and social environment. Special emphasis will be on the impact on women. The recommendations would include a strong case for impact mitigation. This would provide a pool of resources and database for further research and analysis on related issues. The study will compare the expected outcomes with that of other countries where similar studies have been undertaken. The study would help policy makers, influential leaders and society in deepening their understanding of the socio-economic impact of HIV on households and design appropriate policies and programmes to mitigate it. The questionnaire has been adapted from China\u2019s questionnaire with some modifications - eliminated some questions on the mode of transmission keeping in mind the ethnicity of the people and issues of confidentiality and added some new questions on the labour force. The questionnaire is divided into two parts based on the experience in pre-testing in west Java: SDGK09-K7 which is meant for the head of the household, in case he/she does not know that one of his/her household member is infected. It was felt that it was 7 Please refer companion CD ROM for questionnaire 17 Socio-economic impact of HIV at the household levels in Asia and the Pacific not only difficult but also risky to ask about the PLHIV when the other members are not aware about his/her HIV status. This questionnaire will also be used to interview control-households. SDGK09-M8 is meant for the person living with HIV. It was difficult to find the control households. Unlike China, in Indonesia, there was no listing of PLHIV and the control households were selected by comparing household position or the condition of the houses such as the wall, the roof and the number of members in the household with that of HIV households. For the survey, a sample of seven provinces has been selected primarily driven by the estimated number of IDUs, prisoners, and people living with HIV, based on the data that there are 193,000 people living with HIV. The household sample consists of 1,000 households nationwide and proportionally selected from seven provinces. The province selected are intended to represent four high prevalence and two low prevalence provinces -Jakarta, Papua, East Java, West Java, Bali, East Nusa Tenggara and West Nusa Tenggara. East Nusa Tenggara and West Nusa Tenggara are considered as low prevalence provinces. The list of populations/mapping of positive households will be provided by JOTHI (Jar- ingan Orang Terinfeksi HIV Indonesia, PLHIV network in Indonesia). Base on the list the sample households will be selected through systematic sampling. The sampling will seek to ensure all modes of transmission are covered. The enumeration will be conducted by a team consisting of two persons, one, and a staff from the National Statistical Office (NSO) and another from JOTHI. Each team will interview 25 households. The field work will take almost one month if one household is interviewed every day. The staff from the NSO will be responsible for the interview of PLHIV and their household and also interviewing the control households. JOTHI will be responsible, especially, for the access to the PLHIV since they are very sensi- tive to those who are not from their community. Some JOTHI researchers are also participating in coordinating the field enumeration, and observing the quality of data. The quality of data will be supervised by a field supervisor and editor in the office and a validation program will be executed. Discussion To questions on mode of transmission, it was stated that the discussions with UNDP Indonesia and National Commission and also with JOTHI led to the decision not to ask direct questions on mode of transmission for ethical and accuracy reasons. 8 Please refer companion CD ROM for questionnaire 18 RepoRT on TeChniCal ConsulTaTion However, direct questions will be asked on this issue. Regarding the selection of control household, the concern was whether the comparison should be with the socio economic condition of the household before HIV-infection or at present. In terms of comparing with the current condition of the HIV households, there is some information- loss because from the time of getting infected to the present, the household has become poorer. It is very difficult to find the comparison because the household may not correctly", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "9d1e4397-0cf6-41e9-8dec-d4b3661ccb03": {"__data__": {"id_": "9d1e4397-0cf6-41e9-8dec-d4b3661ccb03", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/socio-economic-impact-hiv-household-levels-asia-and-pacific-report-technical-consultation", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Socio-economic imp