 sure that the results of the non-HIV households can be compared with the results for the general population. Mr. Promono said many of the positive respondents refuse to be interviewed at home and they may have to be interviewed outside their homes. This may create some problem since it is important to know the socio-economic condition of the HIV households in order to select the comparable non-HIV households. The participants were unanimous in the utility of the pilot tests, particularly on issues of sensitivity. 19 Socio-economic impact of HIV at the household levels in Asia and the Pacific Socio-economic impact of HIV and AIDS on households in Vietnam: The impact on poverty Tommaso Tabet UNDP, Hanoi, Vietnam T he first study on the impact of HIV in Vietnam was conducted in 2004 and the results were published in 2005. The findings of the study were used for policy and programme decisions of the government. The government was interested to conduct an update of the earlier study, and hence the present project was started in 2008-2009. It comes under the UNDP funded HIV leadership program involving the Party and national assembly. The project began in October in 2008 and was due to be completed by late march 2009, but has been slightly delayed. Both the government and the HIV community in Vietnam have high expectations from the study that the data and information can provide crucial evidence for policy formulation. There have been many changes in the HIV framework in Vietnam in the last three years and it is therefore time to assess the impact. The study is both qualitative and quantitative and is consistent with older studies. It also has a great potential for regional analysis. In the context of Vietnam, its legal framework which provides good HIV laws, the party directive 54, and also the national strategy on HIV go hand in hand. The Three Ones is a pretty new development in Vietnam. Also, importantly, HIV prevalence estimations are more reliable reliable now. All the partners have agreed on the methodology and the results of the study. However, MDG 6 will probably not be achieved by 2010-2015. The Vietnam household questionnaire can be found within the companion CD-ROM. Objectives of the study To assess, analyze and update the nature and magnitude of socio-economic D impacts of HIV and AIDS on households To draw possible scenarios of HIV/AIDS impacts on poverty and draw projec- D tions on what could happen in 5-10 years 21 Socio-economic impact of HIV at the household levels in Asia and the Pacific To develop up-to-date survey and analytical methodologies to demonstrate D the feasibility of the study To feed to the national M&E system and outline the most relevant policy and D advocacy recommendations. The methodology is very similar to other studies, especially those in India and China. Six provinces or cities with high HIV prevalence were selected as the sites. The study-design consists of comparing 453 pairs of HIV affected and non-affected households, and then qualitative in depth interviews for confirmation. To do the sampling, the HIV positive network was approached. The team also worked", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "e47f0e79-7f03-4370-ae73-976097c80001": {"__data__": {"id_": "e47f0e79-7f03-4370-ae73-976097c80001", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/socio-economic-impact-hiv-household-levels-asia-and-pacific-report-technical-consultation", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Socio-economic impact of HIV at the household levels in Asia and the Pacific - Report on Technical Consultation", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Tit