cludes reduction in absolute expenditure on food and education, and an increase in absolute expenditure on medicine and health care. The income losses have been calculated as income lost due to lost working days by caregivers and the sick per- sons. On the social front, PLHIV changed their work because they think that they were not strong enough for their work. Though stigma and discrimination is found to be decreasing, it still exists. It also includes self stigma. Results indicate increased burden on women (care-givers), especially in-house, compared to men. Another finding is that free ARV program and participation in self-help groups may help to minimize the impact of HIV and AIDS on households and individuals. The ARV program was started only about a year or two ago in Vietnam. But there have 22 RepoRT on TeChniCal ConsulTaTion been huge improvements in providing free ARV drugs. The government now fully supports people living with HIV. It has supported the establishment of an umbrella organization of their networks. The framework is very good and the feedback from PLHIV is that they find a considerable support from these groups. Limitations The sample has a loss of representation of the extremes, i.e. respondents in early or last stage of HIV infection, as well as those in the poorest and richest quintiles, because they are very difficult to access. It has also been very difficult to select the non-HIV households which are in the same income quintiles as that of HIV house- holds/or live in similar conditions. There is the question of reliability of income/expenditure estimates. The information provided in the quantitative questionnaires, as also during some of the qualitative discussions indicate that people misquote their income so that they are in the lower income quintile and hence can access free ARV. Consultations are being held on the manner of comparison of the income and expenditure with VHLSS9 income/expen- diture classifications. This is quite important, especially for the projection in the last part of the study. Since the framework of the present study and the methodologies used in 2005 have changed, it is not possible to use the 2005 study either as the baseline or as a comparative tool. Projecting the Impact Projecting the impact of HIV/AIDS on national poverty involves estimation of unit cost of HIV care and treatment services. Some information will be provided by the government, like cost of ARV. The number of households that may fall into poverty as a result of HIV/AIDS will be modelled by projecting HIV incidence in each quin- tile using the national representative data of VHLSS (2008). High and low epidemic growth projections are available and will be utilized. The incidence for each quintile will be combined with household impact data to determine the incidence of pov- erty. Dynamic relationship between poverty and income growth will be taken into account. A range of assumptions underpinning the analysis will be made for GDP growth, cost of inflation, population growth, and income distribution The results of the study will be used in the National monetary and evolution frame- 9 Vietnam Household Living Standards Survey 23 Socio-economic impact of HIV at the household levels in Asia and the Pacific work. It will also be used within the technical working group, especially for discussing the exercise that has been launched recently in Vietnam.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "b3bfc286-3b8a-4954-9459-2435cf3cfc36": {"__data__": {"id_": "b3bfc286-3b8a-4954-9459-2435cf3cfc36", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/socio-economic-impact-hiv-household-levels-asia-and-pacific-report-technical-consultation", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "