whether it is possible to apply it in other places, keeping in mind the limitations. Despite the serious limitations, there is nothing wrong in attempting poverty related projections as it can influence policy makers. 24 RepoRT on TeChniCal ConsulTaTion Socio-economic impact of HIV on households in Cambodia A national study: the methodology and process James Cercone President, Sanigest International I n Cambodia, the study is in progress and hence this meeting is particularly useful for confirming and advancing some of the concerns regarding the questionnaire. The presentation gives an overview of the study designs, some of the key issues regarding mapping and data as well as the key issues and challenges being faced along the way. The objective is to carry out a socio-economic impact survey looking at HIV versus non-HIV households in terms of specific outcomes such as: Deepened understanding of the socio-economic impact 1. of HIV on households. Estimation of the overall economic impact on Cambodia. 2. Identifying appropriate policies and programmes to address 3. the socio-economic impact of HIV. To make recommendations to create an enabling social environment 4. for people living with HIV in Cambodia. The main concern of the study is a deep integration between the results of the study and the translations of the results into policy changes. The study has been under- taken with the support of UNDP and UNAIDS through a consulting company called Sanigest International and a local partner, Center for Advanced Study (Cambodia). The team is working in consultation with different stakeholders (Civil Society, donors, Government of Cambodia, and Development Finance Institutions). The overall design is similar to the other studies. The economic impact of HIV that the study is seeking to measure is at both micro and macro levels. HIV affects the individuals, households, the demography, mortality, morbidity the labour market, the private sector, the government and ultimately the economy. This structure or 25 Socio-economic impact of HIV at the household levels in Asia and the Pacific framework has been used to try and develop the questionnaire, and to ensure that all the key elements are captured. So far, none of the studies have discussed about the impact on businesses risks. The impact on household can be grouped into three categories - economic, social and health. It can be then broken down to create what essentially are the modules for income and employment issues, social support programmes, consumption and savings, health status, education, knowledge and awareness, gender, and household coping mechanisms. This study has two addi- tional areas of intervention-economic shock and food security. How these are to be included into the overall framework is yet to be worked out. The main research questions are: How does HIV affect the human capital accumulation in a household, includ- 1. ing education, nutrition and health outcomes? Some questions on nutrition (body mass index and growth) are being asked so that the differences in some of these key measures between HIV and non-HIV households can be seen. What is the direct impact of HIV on poverty, social structure, migration and 2. inequality including specific issues of gender and access to financial services? What is the impact of HIV on labour supply and wages due to morbidity, 3. death and discrimination? How the level and pattern of consumption compare for HIV households and 4. non-HIV households? How does stigma and discrimination associated with HIV affect household be- 5. haviour and outcomes, how does it reduce the efficacy of", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "1577137e-13fc-4cdd-99bf-910bc52cc5e5": {"__data__": {"id_": "1577137e-13fc-4cdd-99bf-910bc52cc5e5", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacif