empt has also been made to be consistent with the Cambodian socio-economic survey. Regarding the questionnaire, both English and Khmer translations are being used to capture the nuances. The Cambodian household questionnaire can be found in the companion CD-ROM The Process The sample is to be selected randomly from the registry at the ART/OI sites, which have information on HIV households. Home-based teams and interviewers will be used to carry out the survey. Twenty out of 24 provinces are being covered, and hence unlike the other surveys which are taking a targeted approach of selecting the low and high prevalence areas, this study will go in for a national representation. A number of power estimates have been done to try and improve the precision in terms of the size of the sample. If the home based teams were to apply the survey instrument, supervision will be very important. Across the board, the various studies have a sample size ranging from 1000 to 3000. For example, if the difference in the hospitalization rates between the HIV and non-HIV households are to be assessed, what should be the sample size? For the hospitalization rates, which are a fairly infrequent, (e.g. only 5 percent people need hospitalization) by increasing the sample size from 1000 to 2000, there will be a huge gain. However, an increase in the sample size from 2000 to 2500, the gain is small, and from 2500 to 3000, it is very small. On the other hand, in the case of the household savings rate, there is no improvement in the results by considering above 250 households. Hence it is very important to model specifically based on the parameters one is looking for and try to determine the optimum sample size rather than setting an overall sample size which is generally done. The initial sample size was 2000 HIV households and 2000 control households. After running a number of power estimates with greater precision, and using the results from China and India, the calibrated model ended up with a much bigger sample of HIV households rather than the control households because more precision was required with regard to HIV households. Secondly, because of the consistency with the Cambodia socio-economic survey (CSES), it is felt that the CSES can be used as well to counter the small sample size of the control households. A number of other 27 Socio-economic impact of HIV at the household levels in Asia and the Pacific questions, for example on the education and income levels, can be compared with the CSES and it should be possible to make the comparison between the HIV house- holds and the non-HIV households. The study is also assuming the response rate to be 90 percent. It is also important to know about the replacement rates. I will have five data sources: the primary data collected from the ART/OI site registries, \u201crandom walk\u201d mapping to select the control groups for which information will be taken from administrative data from registered lists, the national CSES10 to validate the results for non-HIV households, focus groups to understand better some of the key results for specific groups and finally, direct interviews for higher income groups. In India and China, the high income group was under-represented. The process of ethical review has not been very transparent and is very time consum- ing. The quality of the registry of the PLHIV is not really known. Though the study team has been assured of it, they are not sure whether they can randomize the selection of the households. High levels of migration or the inability to locate the people", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "c70718ef-fe18-4b76-ba49-543c4a97c156": {"__data__": {"id_": "c70718ef-fe18-4b76-ba49-543c4a97c156", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/socio-economic-impact-hiv-household-