use- hold characteristics such as occupation and income. If the number of households so 10 Combodia Socio-Economic Survey 28 RepoRT on TeChniCal ConsulTaTion obtained was more than three for every positive household, the stochastic manner was followed. If the quality of registry of HIV household was not satisfactory, other lists either with the government or some other group was looked at. Regarding the power of test sampling, the Chinese study used the formula where sampling error and confidence interval were given. Therefore, the power of testing was implicit. Increasing the sample size beyond a level doesn\u2019t result in any scientific gain but rising costs. The Chinese method takes that into account. On the issue of high income sample, the study in Cambodia is not proposing to achieve a representative sample to include them in any significant way, but to in- terview 5-6 high income persons who can be identified through personal contacts and use it to make anecdotal references to see potential differences between HIV in high income households Vs HIV in middle or low income households. In terms of the power estimates, a linear programming was done to find out the optimum sample size to get a minimum confidence level and use the evidence from the previous studies. 29 Socio-economic impact of HIV at the household levels in Asia and the Pacific HIV and food security in Asia - preliminary findings from the existing studies and implications for future studies Kazuyuki Uji UNDP Regional Centre In Colombo, Sri Lanka T his is an unexplored area and the socio-economic impact studies that are be- ing undertaken now can certainly provide a great opportunity to deepen the understanding of the subject. The presentation is to explore possible questions or possible analysis that could be considered for these studies. Based on a preliminary review of existing data from within Asia, the presentation would try to look in to the issue of HIV and food security. In the last few years in the Asia-pacific region, there has been a sharp increase in the price of food and fuel. The extent of price increase has been particularly sharp and some people call the phenomenon the \u2018Silent Tsunami\u2019 denoting massive possible impacts of hunger across the region. There is a sudden steep increase in the food prices. Given these circumstances of rising food prices, people have started to think about the issue of hunger or food insecurity in the context of HIV. The primary review of existing literature indicates that the linkages of HIV and food insecurity have been firmly established in Africa. In Africa, food insecurity is acting both as a potential cause as well as consequence of vulnerability to HIV. However, in Asia these linkages have not been extensively explored, despite the fact that for example in Cambodia, the overall food programme categorizes the HIV-affected households as food-insecure. In addition, food insecurity could cause massive clinical impact on the HIV positive people and the affected households. For example, the malnutrition triggered by the food insecurity increases the risk of OIs as well as fastens the rate of disease progression to AIDS, increases the risks of vertical transmission, and renders children with HIV, who are prone to severe malnutrition, at high risk. It is known to obstruct the absorption of HIV medicines, which is particularly concerning because ARV is a lifeline of the positive people to stay healthy and keep working to support children and family. Therefore, these points are very important not only", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "d37a4e85-afad-4a5b-8187-cde44a842dd5": {"__data__": {"id_": "d37a4e85-afad-4a5b-8187-cde44a842dd5", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/socio-economic-impact-hiv-household-levels-asia-and-pacific-report-technical-consultation", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Socio-economic impact of HIV at the household levels in Asia and the Pacific - Report on Technical Consultation", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/socio-economic-impact-hiv-household-levels-asia-and-pacific-report-technical-consultation", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "484cb00ff10383d17093a7f29dc8b019cd574305c3e157a4169a27741681419f"}}, "hash": "484cb00ff10383d17093a7f29dc8b019cd574305c3e157a4169a27741681419f", "text": "when one looks at them from a clinical per- spectives, but also from the perspective of care, support and impact mitigation. Given 31 Socio-economic impact of HIV at the household levels in Asia and the Pacific these extraordinary circumstances of rising food prices and the compelling evidence from Africa and potential far-reaching impacts of food insecurity in the context of HIV, there is a need for some information from within Asia. In this regard, a preliminary study was commissioned to the Mahidol University, Thailand to examine the existing data from within Asia to find out possible linkages or information on this subject. Two types of studies were conducted. First was the collection of household studies which had HIV-affected as well as non-HIV affected households including the HIV household studies from India and China and a house- hold study in Thailand, which was conducted in 1998. Other studies used were the Cambodian household study of 2003 and 2004, published last year in the AIDS Journal; the Vietnam HIV poverty study (commissioned by UNDP Vietnam);Cambodia Food Support Programme evaluation report commissioned by USAID; and the Tamil Nadu study on the socio-economic impact of ART. This is the only cohort study and the rest are cross-sectional. Of course, there are so many limitations because of the reliance on existing data. A major limitation was that none of the studies was actually designed to specifically target the food insecurity issues. Despite these major limitations, there are interesting findings which may have use- ful implications for the socio-economic impact studies. Though the data cannot be compared across the board, the data on the per capita monthly food expenditure in India, Thailand and China show that sometimes there are specific variations in terms of food expenditure. For example, in India the HIV affected households had actually spent more as compared with non-HIV affected households and the report speculates that HIV affected households would spend more on nutritional food to stay healthy. On the other hand, in Thailand, it is the opposite where the HIV affected households spent less as compared to the control or non-HIV affected households. From the food security perspective, in the context of rising food prices, one could argue that HIV af- fected households in India could be more vulnerable because the rising food prices may force these households to cut down the food consumption needed to stay healthy. On the other hand, one could also argue that the HIV affected households in Thailand spending less could be considered more vulnerable, because of the rising medical expenses for the HIV affected households compared to non-HIV households may have pushed down the priority on food which has been strained by the rising prices. The basis of the data alone no conclusive statement can be made. One way of ad- dressing this issue is to examine whether the food expenditure patterns or levels have changed after diagnosis or disclosure, and if yes, when. This is subject to recall bias, but may be interesting to explore. Another interesting finding came from the Cambodian household study (2003). The data shows that the percentage of households that pur- 32 RepoRT on TeChniCal ConsulTaTion chased less food to pay for their healthcare is higher for the HIV affected households, suggesting that the HIV affected households are more vulnerable. The same study also demonstrates that children and adolescents in HIV affected households recorded some food security issues such as experiencing more hunger, and consuming fewer meals a day. This shows how food reduction is used as a coping mechanism and how it could impact the weaker or younger family members. To address this issue, the pos- sible question and analysis that could be considered is that how many meals they have a day. This could be directed at children, adolescents or female members if they are included in the study. One could also go into the quality of the meals. The Cambodia Food Support Evaluation Report shows some potential benefits of food support to HIV affected households. The study shows much lower medical expenditure for the HIV affected households in the intervention which received food support as compared with the control group which did not receive any such food support. The data from the same study showing lower medical expenses for the intervention group also shows that the percentage of people living with HIV and reporting at least one infection in the past two weeks is lower for the intervention group and this definitely reduces the need for hospital visits, doctor\u2019s fees or medicines. Given almost the same expenditure levels between the control and intervention groups, the savings", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "c553a9d6-1e76-4b39-9d08-8f4a385e6174": {"__data__": {"id_": "c553a9d6-1e76-4b39-9d08-8f4a385e6174", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publ