hey consume all the support received? Did they receive any training/information on diet and nutrition along with the food sup- port? One could also look into the potential impact of the food support, the change in the food consumption or expenditure patterns as a result of food support. The Tamil Nadu cohort study on the socio-economic impact of the ART on the adult PLHIV in the Tamil Nadu Family Care Continuum Programme appears to show that ART initiation is somehow connected with the increasing food consumption. However, since the details of the study are not available, no statistical significance could be assessed. 33 Socio-economic impact of HIV at the household levels in Asia and the Pacific Increased food consumption levels seem to be more of an indirect consequence of initiation of ART which made the people healthy, and stay on their jobs for a steady income. The possible interplay between the ART and food security may be an area worth exploring because more and more people in Asia are starting on ART. Suggestions for further analysis/possible additional questions for the survey It may be interesting to run a regression to see which variables may be associ- D ated with food security risks and food support. To capture changes in the household food consumption after detecting the D HIV status, including intra-household differences, following questions can be tried. Did the food expenditure/consumption pattern of the HIV households change \ufffd after diagnosis/disclosure? If yes, Why? And How? If not, Why not? \ufffd When? \u2022\ufffd How many meals do you have a day? \u2022\ufffd Adults \ufffd Children/adolescents \ufffd \ufffd Female members Has the number of meals changed since diagnosis/disclosure? \ufffd What do you have for these meals? \ufffd Has the content of the meals changed? \ufffd On the quality aspect of food support programme, the following may be D asked: What food support do you receive? \ufffd Do you consume all the food you receive? \ufffd D