 impact of HIV at the household levels in Asia and the Pacific The economic implications in terms of GDP are very significant. The global growth rate decelerated from 5.2% in 2007 to 3.4% in 2008, and in 2009 it is going to be only 0.5%, which is about 4-5% decline since 2007. Asia may also witness a similar decline, i.e. half of what has been achieved in 2007. Asia was able to achieve about 9-10% growth in 2007 and 9% in 2008. In 2007, China was able to grow at 12-13% while India recorded a growth rate of 9%. But in 2009, Asia will be lucky if it is able to achieve 5% growth. The growth is expected to remain at or above the rates observed during the Asian financial crisis. Impact on the labour market is felt not only in Asia but also at the global level. Unemployment is increasing dramatically in the last 2 years. The number of unem- ployed people in Asia has risen from 79 million in 2007 to 84 million in 2008 and is expected to go up to 94 million in 2009. Even though unemployment is increasing, Asian countries are still able to offer good number of employment opportunities compared to other developing countries. For example, in 2008, more than half of world\u2019s new employment was created in Asia. Unfortunately most of this employment was not remunerated properly. 47% of the employed (over 250 million) in South Asia are classified as working poor, compared to the global average of 20%. On the poverty side, Asia still has about 900 million poor people, even though dur- ing the last 15-20 years Asia has experienced a dramatic decline not only in terms of reducing poverty incidence but also by lifting millions of people out of poverty. But during this financial crisis, the fuel and food prices put together, the two exter- nal shocks are expected to push roughly 100 million people below poverty line i.e. roughly about 60-70 million people minimum on the financial side, another 50-60 million due to food and fuel prices. With about 100 million additional people below the poverty line, the total could go up from 900 million to a billion. In all the developing regions, during last 2-3 years the number of people affected by hunger is increasing dramatically from roughly about 800 to about 963 million people, which is an increase of about 150 million people. Most of this increase is taking place in Asia and so the financial crisis could create further problems on this front. In terms of policy response and in order to mitigate the impact, many countries, both developed and developing, across the world have taken strong fiscal and monetary stimulus policy packages. This fiscal stimulus alone now roughly constitutes about 1.5% of the GDP - East Asia still has a large fiscal space to boost the economy, but unfortunately many South Asian countries have relatively higher fiscal deficit. The monetary policy has also changed dramatically. Even in 2008, it was becoming more 36 RepoRT on TeChniCal ConsulTaTion complex because until September, many countries tried to use the monetary policies to control inflation such as the food and fuel inflation. But in the last four months they went to other extreme: they went on expanding monetary policies to support the economic growth under the global economic outlook. In terms of policy challenges, many countries will have lower export growth, lower economic growth and higher unemployment rate. Similar is the case with the pov- erty rates. The key issue is the possible duration of the global recession. If it exceeds six months, the region will face serious problems. Another key challenge is the", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "7629126d-bf0f-412a-816a-0837cc59938f": {"__data__": {"id_": "7629126d-bf0f-412a-816a-0837cc59938f", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/socio-economic-impact-hiv-household-l