alth and other basic needs of the general popula- tion are addressed. In this regard, UNDP should promote/encourage countries to institute conditional social development programmes similar to India\u2019s employment guarantee programme. Discussion People in rural areas can get affected indirectly by the loss of jobs in urban areas. In urban areas, a large number of people working in sectors such as tourism, construc- tion, textile and garments are migrants from rural areas and when they lose jobs they will go back to the villages. In India, for e.g. hundreds of people working in gem and jewellery industry in Gujarat, are moving back to rural areas. It is a very good opportunity for using the stimulus packages of the government for social sector since private sector is not stepping in because of the high risk and profit reduc- tion. However there are doubts about the absorption capacity of the social sector. Government support to HIV/AIDS may probably decline more allocation may go to addressing the financial crisis. The HIV/AIDS household is likely to be affected mainly through three primary in- struments/channels: employment, support of national/international NGOs PLHIV, treatment programmes etc, and government support. There is a need to examine the fiscal stimulus package announced by various countries and see the nature of 37 Socio-economic impact of HIV at the household levels in Asia and the Pacific social safety net provided to the HIV households. In this regard, the findings from the China study about the different types of support to the HIV households and their impact are very interesting. From Cambodia, there is evidence on the wide rang- ing impact of food support. What would be the impact on agricultural production? Studies in Uganda have shown that HIV households tend to shift from multi-crops to single crops resulting in serious drop in household incomes. 38 RepoRT on TeChniCal ConsulTaTion Spousal Transmission of HIV An example focused on intimate partner violence and HIV infection: findings from a national sample of Indian husband-wife Dyads (Presented via tele-conference) Michele R. Decker, ScD11 ,George R. Seage, III ScD12, Anita Raj, PhD13, Niranjan Saggurti, PhD14, Donta Balaiah, MSc, PhD15, Jay G. Silverman, PhD16 Harvard School of Public Health, Boston Introduction Relation between IPV and HIV I t is estimated that one in three women worldwide face violence at the hands of a partner. The abused women demonstrate high levels of HIV probably because of limited ability to refuse sex and negotiate condom use. Further, behavioral interventions are successful with non-abused women and are found ineffective for abused women. Young people in the age group of 15-24 years constitute almost half of new STI infections each year. Perhaps the most telling evidence is that suggesting that elements of STI/HIV protection are outside the domain of control of women in abusive relationships. Some evidence from qualitative work with women and prior work among men suggest that IPV relates to coercive sexual risk. Abusive men report more risky sexual behavior and demonstrate higher prevalence of self-reported STI. Men\u2019s abusive and sexual risk behaviors may elevate their own STI/HIV risk and facilitate transmission to female partners. The available data have prompted increasing recognition of pathways by which male violence against female partners may both be a marker for and directly facilitate (i.e.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "a7024b95-75c0-4f30-aca7-e1579e959e7c": {"__data__": {"id_": "a7024b95-75c0-4f30-aca7-e1579e959e7c", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/socio-economic-impact-hiv-household-levels-asia-and-pacific-report-technical-consultation", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Socio-economic impact of HIV at the household levels in Asia and the Pacific - Report on Technical Consultation", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/socio-economic-impact-hiv-household-levels-asia-and-pacific-report-technical-consultation", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "3a2bdfe8c7d237c65ad7b8151b4443c682d714da50e32f7ad4276cf71aca64cf"}, "2": {"node_id": "7629126d-bf0f-412a-816a-0837cc59938f", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/socio-economic-impact-hiv-household-levels-asia-and-pacific-report-technical-consultation", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "3aca8e3258bca5d29c2d66c450b705ee188af494baf7fa7628b3923625d7c7e6"}}, "hash": "6829dde0a1e792693290fffba89670c17a12ff2f81a90064904999e0f832c53b", "text": "11 Harvard School of Public Health, (Boston, MA, USA) 12 Harvard School of Public Health, (Boston, MA, USA) 13 Boston University of Public Health (Boston, MA, USA) 14 Population Council (New Delhi, India) 15 National Institute for Research in Reproductive Health, Indian Council for Medical Research (Mumbai, India) 16 Harvard School of Public Health, (Boston, MA, USA) 39 Socio-economic impact of HIV at the household levels in Asia and the Pacific be a mechanism for) sexual transmission of HIV to women in India and elsewhere. Specifically, the extramarital high-risk sexual behavior of abusive men appears to relate to a higher prevalence of HIV among this group; thus, IPV may act as a risk marker in that it relates", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "e236b9a5-7ebc-4627-99cf-db672e997aae": {"__data__": {"id_": "e236b9a5-7ebc-4627-99cf-db672e997aae", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/socio-economic-impact-hiv-household-levels-asia-and-pacific-report-technical-consultation", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Socio-economic impact of HIV at the household levels in Asia and the Pacific - Report on Technical Consultation", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/socio-economic-impact-hiv-household-levels-asia-and-pacific-report-technical-consultation", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "3f29df9dc6bb3a461b8e3e85a44c4064f081ff7e7ecc387263e59f9f382ca7fe"}}, "hash": "3f29df9dc6bb3a461b8e3e85a44c4064f081ff7e7ecc387263e59f9f382ca7fe", "text": "to the higher likelihood of an infected partner. However, unprotected forced sex or unprotected coercive sex perpetrated by abusive men within marriage may constitute a direct mechanism, possibly facilitating HIV trans- mission to wives. In India, heterosexual sex is considered to be the dominant route for transmission of HIV. Married women were once considered low-risk because of the limited sexual risk behavior among women. Despite reduction in prevalence of HIV infection among the general population of India, women account for a rising percentage of all cases with husbands' risk behavior described as the major source. Women comprise 40% of the reported 2.5 million cases of HIV in India. Intimate partner violence (IPV) has been described as being associated with heterosexual transmission of HIV to women in India and elsewhere. The above study was undertaken with the objective of assessing the relationship between experiencing IPV and the occurrence of HIV infection in a nationally representative sample of married Indian women tested for HIV. In this first national population-based study of the relationship of husbands' violence against wives to the latter\u2019s HIV status (as indicated via diagnostic testing), married Indian women who experienced both physical and sexual IPV demonstrated HIV infec- tion prevalence approximately four times greater than that of non abused women. Importantly, women's HIV infection was not related to their own sexual risk behaviors (condom use and multiple partnering). These findings support descriptions of the Indian HIV epidemic among married women as driven primarily by the behavior of men and highlight the potential role of men's abusive behaviors in posing HIV risk to their female partners. As abusive men have been found to demonstrate both higher levels of sexual risk behavior and, as an inherent aspect of their abuse, higher levels of control over sex and sexual protection, women experiencing IPV face \"double jeopardy\" regarding risk for HIV infection from male partners (i.e. they are likely to hold little control over sexual protection with a high-risk male partner). Thus, IPV may represent both a risk marker and risk factor for increased HIV prevalence among women. Current findings of Indian women's elevated HIV infection based on their reports of physical and sexual violence from their husbands demonstrate the need for further research to confirm the specific potential mechanisms and to disentangle the roles of abusive men's risky behavior outside the relationship and sexual violence within the relationship in posing HIV risk to their female partners. 40 RepoRT on TeChniCal ConsulTaTion Aims of the study Are abusive men more likely to be infected? 1. D Assess the linkage between IPV perpetration with men\u2019s HIV infection Does IPV modify women\u2019s HIV risk, based on exposure to husband HIV? 2. Assess women\u2019s risk of HIV infection based on exposure to husband\u2019s HIV D Assess role of IPV in modifying women\u2019s risk D The present study attempts to advance the current state of knowledge by assessing the prevalence of HIV infection among married Indian women and evaluating the relationship of women's experiences of physical and sexual violence from husbands to their HIV infection. Data The present study is based on data from the National Family Health Survey -3 (NFHS-3), a national survey conducted in all 29 states of India from November 2005 to August 2006 by the International Institute for Population Sciences and Macro International. A nationally representative household-based sample was created via a stratified, multistage cluster sampling strategy. The analytic sample was limited to currently married female participants for whom both outcome (HIV test results) and exposure data (IPV) were available, and the final sample consisted of 20429 couples. The predictor variable considered was the physical or sexual IPV and was based on 9-item assessment via women\u2019s self report. The outcome variable considered was HIV and was assessed on biological sample collection and lab testing for HIV-1. In addition, demographic covariants considered were age, education, wealth index and religion while sexual risk was assessed by condom non-use, multiple past-year sex partners and male circumcision. Step -1 of Analysis In order to analyse IPV as a risk marker for high risk male partner, men\u2019s risk of HIV acquisition outside the marital relationship based on their perpetration of IPV was assessed. To allow for greatest clarity and empirical strength in assessing the extent to which men\u2019s IPV perpetration relates to acquisition of HIV infection outside the cur- rent marital relationship, as hypothesized, this analysis was restricted to men whose female marital partners were not infected with HIV, i.e., those men who could not have acquired HIV via their female partners (n=20,362). For this 67 men whose wives were HIV+ (n=20362) were removed to minimize", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "238290ba-852e-410a-be53-bf0297e6be8b": {"__data__": {"id_": "238290ba-852e-410a-be53-bf0297e6be8b", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/socio-economic-impact-hiv-household-levels-asia-and-pacific-report-technical-consultation", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Socio-economic impact of HIV at the household levels in Asia and the Pacific - Report on Technical Consultation", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/socio-economic-impact-hiv-household-levels-asia-and-pacific-report-technical-consultation", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "92aeec2b8741afc21106260133a225891c82e223c5372d9513eb4b838a0aa81c"}}, "hash": "92aeec2b8741afc21106260133a225891c82e223c5372d9513eb4b838a0aa81c", "text": "the likelihood that they were infected by their wives. Men\u2019s HIV prevalence based on IPV perpetration was found to be 1.90 times that of non-IPV giving greater strength to the suggestion that abusive men\u2019s sexual risk behavior outside that relationship is leading them to acquire HIV. 41 Socio-economic impact of HIV at the household levels in Asia and the Pacific Step - 2 of Analysis In order to analyse IPV as a risk factor for HIV transmission, women\u2019s risk of HIV infection based on exposure to husband\u2019s HIV was assessed. This was stratified by presence of IPV and also formally tested for interactive effect of exposure to both husband\u2019s HIV and IPV. Associations of husband\u2019s HIV with women\u2019s HIV, stratified by IPV shows nearly 7 fold greater risk of acquiring HIV. Key Findings Abusive men are almost twice as likely to acquire HIV outside the marital D relationship Wives of these men are at greater risk for acquisition as these men are more \ufffd likely to be infected IPV appears to facilitate spousal transmission D Women exposed to both IPV and husband\u2019s HIV increases their HIV risk over \ufffd and above exposure to husband HIV alone by a factor of 7 Evidence supports both elements of double jeopardy in posing HIV risk to D abused women in the Indian context Implications Integrated prevention efforts for HIV and violence perpetration are needed. D This could be achieved by Sexual risk reduction targeting IPV perpetrators and behavioral interventions D to prevent IPV may reduce secondary HIV transmission Because of relatively strong gender-based constraints on women's sexual behavior in South Asia, Indian women have little opportunity and great costs associated with sexual risk-taking; thus, their HIV infection is likely to be driven to a greater extent by husbands' behavior (that is, extramarital sexual risk and marital sexual violence). Further, IPV may pose a relatively greater HIV threat to Indian married women based on a lack of communication regarding sex being a culturally prescribed marital norm, posing additional barriers to both discussion of sexual risk and women's resistance to sexual violence. Thus, consideration of cultural and geographic contexts in such investigations is likely to be critical to advancing understanding of how men's IPV, men's sexual risk, and women's sexual risk interact in relating to HIV infection across populations. Current evidence of elevated HIV prevalence among abused women holds critical implications for practice. Clinicians should incorporate inquiries to women regarding 42 RepoRT on TeChniCal ConsulTaTion experiences of partner violence, particularly those working in settings focused on care for STIs, as such infection may be considered a marker for elevated risk of both IPV and HIV. As important as identifying abused women, however, is education regard- ing the nature of their risk and assistance to reduce this risk; thus, greater support for community-based programs supporting women surviving IPV is also required. Further, clinical programs addressing STI/HIV among men should include a focus on IPV as a potential transmission risk for their female partners. However, what will likely be critical to the ability of such programs to reduce men's risk of transmission is the modification of gender norms that have been described as supporting both sexual risk and IPV. Challenges in Research on Spousal HIV Transmission Using couples as the unit of sampling and/or analysis is ideal D Sampling D Identifying incident infection is best \ufffd Low population prevalence of HIV D Need for large numbers of discordant couples \ufffd Testing and disclosure between couples D Need for longitudinal data. D Possible questions on spousal transmission to be included in the sample questionnaire (If both husband and wife are HIV+ - and not already assessed) Who was 1. infected first? (For husband) During the past year, how often did you use a condom when 2. you and your wife had sex? (I did not have sex with my wife in the past year, I used a condom every time, I used a condom most of the time, I used a con- dom some of the time, I used a condom none of the time) (For wife) During the past year, did you ever ask your husband to use a con- 3. dom? (If yes) When you asked him to use a condom, did he use one? (For wife) When you do not want to have sex, but your husband insists, how 4. often are you able to refuse him? (my husband never insists on having sex, I never refuse him, I refuse him some of the time, I refuse him most of the time, I always refuse him) (For wife) Has your husband ever used", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "6fc398b9-10fd-4970-96f8-d38d5cfdd41f": {"__data__": {"id_": "6fc398b9-10fd-4970-96f8-d38d5cfdd41f", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/socio-economic-impact-hiv-household-levels-asia-and-pacific-report-technical-consultation", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Socio-economic impact of HIV at the household levels in Asia and the Pacific - Report on Technical Consultation", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/socio-economic-impact-hiv-household-levels-asia-and-pacific-report-technical-consultation", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "53c5990c96ec0092e9710d86aa4c5201628bd6a836bc11b8eca625368fbd867e"}, "3": {"node_id": "e32893aa-3542-4796-a7df-3789a8cb783d", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/socio-economic-impact-hiv-household-levels-asia-and-pacific-report-technical-consultation", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "00ee422db586f90270c060fc80addcf4134d7b3bb183ab26dcb1d686c964b3d1"}}, "hash": "d6be22c6791eeffa7c8549e8ddcf44671a953475ec6a96c80926b83dd037d2c0", "text": "physical force to make you have sex 5. when you did not want to? (If yes) Did this occur in the past year? (For wife) Have you ever experienced vaginal bleeding after s